    {
      "title": "Biot-Savart's Law",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Biot-Savart Law&nbsp;</strong></h3><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"215\" height=\"167\">&nbsp;</p><p>$\\vec{r}\\equiv$ position vector directed to the point from the current element.</p><p>where $\\frac{{{\\mu }_{0}}}{4\\pi }={{10}^{-7}}\\frac{\\text{T}-\\text{m}}{\\text{A}}$</p><p>Note: Magnitude of $\\overrightarrow{\\text{dB}}$ is given by,</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} {} &amp; &nbsp;\\left| \\overrightarrow{\\text{dB}} \\right|=\\frac{{{\\mu }_{0}}}{4\\pi }\\frac{\\text{idlsin}\\theta }{{{\\text{r}}^{2}}} \\\\ {} &amp; &nbsp;\\left| \\overrightarrow{\\text{dB}} \\right|=0 \\text{ at } \\theta =0 &nbsp;\\text{ or } 180 \\text{ and } \\text{ maximum } \\text{ at } \\theta =90 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>When the charged particle is moving and the field created (magnetic) due to its motion is given by</p><p>$\\overrightarrow{\\text{dB}}=\\left( \\frac{{{\\mu }_{0}}}{4\\pi } \\right)\\left[ \\frac{\\text{q}\\left( \\vec{v}\\times \\vec{r} \\right)}{{{\\text{r}}^{3}}} \\right]\\left( \\text{q } \\text{ is } \\text{ very } \\text{ small} &nbsp;\\right)$</p><p>$\\therefore &nbsp;\\left[ \\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} \\text{i}\\overrightarrow{\\text{dl}}=\\left( \\frac{\\text{d}Q}{\\text{dt}} \\right)\\overrightarrow{\\text{dl}} \\\\ \\text{i}\\overrightarrow{\\text{dl}}=\\text{dQ}\\left( \\frac{\\overrightarrow{\\text{dl}}}{\\text{dt}} \\right)=\\text{dQ}\\vec{v}=\\text{q}\\vec{v} \\\\ \\end{array} \\right]$</p><p>Here, ${{\\mu }_{0}}=$ permeability of free space</p><p>$=4\\pi \\times {{10}^{-7}}\\frac{\\text{T}-\\text{m}}{\\text{A}}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db62c03b9dcaf1afe184"
    },
    {
      "title": "Ampere's Circuital Law ",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Ampere's Circuital Law&nbsp;</strong></h3><p><strong>Statement. </strong>The circulation of magnetic field along a closed loop is ${{\\mu }_{0}}$ times the total current passing through normally, of the area of the closed loop.</p><p>$ $</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"218\" height=\"143\">&nbsp;</p><p>This law is analogous to Gauss Law already covered in electrostatics.</p><p><strong>Important points to note:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>(a) The direction of circulation is assumed to be positive and accordingly any current in the direction of circulation will be positive and the other negative.</p><p>(b) If the current is at an angle $\\theta $ with the plane of the loop, then take its two components, one parallel to the loop, and the other perpendicular to the loop. Consider only the normal component in the formula.</p><p>(c) The above form of Ampere's Law is not valid when the electric field through the area of loop is not constant.</p><p>In that case we need to apply the modified form of Ampere's Law, called <strong>Maxwell Ampere's Law. $ $&nbsp;</strong></p><p>The term $\\frac{\\text{d}{{\\phi }_{\\text{E}}}}{\\text{dt}}{{\\in }_{0}}$ is called as <strong>displacement current.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>(d) Note that in the Ampere's formula, $\\vec{B}$ is due to all the elements in the space, but I contains the summation of the enclosed currents.</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db62c03b9dcaf1afe185"
    }
  ],
